

You should also read FCDO’s overall travel advice and safety and security advice.
The border with Burundi has been closed since January 2024. Border crossings into the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) and Uganda have temporarily closed at short notice in recent years. Be aware of the impact that short-notice border closures could have on any travel plans in the region.
Rwanda-DRC border
The security situation near Rwanda’s borders with DRC remains unstable. Fighting has intensified in eastern DRC near to the Rwandan border. Armed group M23 have expressed their intent to occupy the city of Goma in eastern DRC, which is 500m from the Rwandan border and the Rwandan town of Gisenyi. The FCDO currently advises against all travel to Goma. Keep up to date with developments through your tour operator or local media. 
The border crossings between Rwanda and DRC at Gisenyi-Goma could close at short notice. Your travel insurance could be invalidated if you travel to an area where FCDO advises against travel.
In recent years, armed incursions have occurred into south-west Rwanda:
on 18 June 2023, 2 people were killed and 6 were injured when suspected militants opened fire on a public passenger bus on Nyamagabe-Rusizi road, in Nyungwe Forest, Nyamgabe District
on 17 June 2023, a Congolese soldier crossed into Rwanda at Gisenyi and fired on civilians and Rwandan security personnel near the border, injuring 2 Rwandan police officers – the soldier was shot dead
in 2022, artillery fire from the DRC hit Rwandan territory, close to the border in Kinigi sector of Musanze District in the north-west
If you’re travelling near the DRC or Burundi borders, be aware of the risk of cross-border attacks and government security operations.
Rwanda-Burundi border
The situation in Burundi remains unstable. Tensions along the Rwanda-Burundi border remain high. Both sides have accused the other of cross-border raids targeting local inhabitants.
